e":"Nicholas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of the post-classical Greek personal name <i>Nikolaos</i>, derived from <i>nikē</i> ‘victory’ + <i>laos</i> ‘people’. The spelling with <i>-ch-</i> first occurred as early as the 12th century, and became firmly established at the time of the Reformation, although  <b>Nicolas</b>  is still occasionally found.  St Nicholas  was a 4th-century bishop of Myra in Lycia, about whom virtually nothing factual is known, although a vast body of legend grew up around him, and he became the patron saint of Greece and of Russia, as well as of children, sailors, merchants, and pawnbrokers. His feast day is  6 December , and among the many roles which legend has assigned to him is that of bringer of Christmas presents, in the guise of ‘Santa Claus’ (an alteration of the Dutch form of his name, <i>Sinterklaas</i>)."],"variants":[{"name":"Nickolas","meanings":["Mainly U.S.: variant spelling of   Nicholas  , influenced by the short form   Nick ."]},{"name":"Nicolas","meanings":["From Late Greek.  See  <b>Nicholas</b> ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Nicholas De Rigmaiden I was born about 1179, in Lancaster, Lancashire, England, United Kingdom, his father, John De Rigmaiden I, was 27 and his mother, Crofte, was 25. He married De Barton about 1197, in England, United Kingdom. They were the parents of at least 1 son."},"et":{"Abt 1179–":"umbes 1179–Surnud","1179–Male":"1179–Surnud","1181–Female":"1181–Surnud","1206–1305":"1206–1305","1154–Male":"1154–Surnud","1156–Female":"1156–Surnud","Abt 1197":"umbes 1197","1305":"1305","1206":"1206","Abt 1179":"umbes 1179","before 1179":"enne 1179","1179":"1179","1156":"1156","1154":"1154","1181":"1181","Abt 1206":"umbes 1206","Lancaster, Lancashire, England":"Lancaster, Lancashire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","England":"England"},"fi":{"Abt 1179–":"noin 1179–Kuollut","1179–Male":"1179–Kuollut","1181–Female":"1181–Kuo